      analysis: '"One body" \u2014 organic metaphor presenting society as a single living organism where every part depends on every other. "Members" implies belonging you cannot opt out of. The repetition of "we are" is deliberately inclusive \u2014 no exceptions, no escape clause. The parallelism (identical sentence structures) gives his words the rhythm of a sermon or political speech. This is Priestley\'s thesis delivered directly: society is collective, not individual. Structurally, this speech is the mirror-opposite of Birling\'s "a man has to look after himself" in Act 1 \u2014 the entire play exists between these two competing philosophies.',
      context: 'Priestley was a committed socialist who helped found the Common Wealth Party. Written in 1945 as the Labour landslide approached, the Inspector voices Priestley\'s hope that post-war Britain would choose Attlee\'s welfare state over a return to Birling\'s pre-war individualism. The 1945 audience had experienced collective wartime sacrifice \u2014 the Inspector\'s words validated what they already knew.',
