      analysis: '"Absolutely" \u2014 the superlative intensifier makes his confidence total and therefore totally wrong. The repetition of "unsinkable" hammers home his certainty. Priestley weaponises dramatic irony: every person in the 1945 audience knew the Titanic sank on its maiden voyage in April 1912 with 1,500 deaths. This isn\'t just wrong \u2014 it\'s cataclysmically wrong. The effect is that everything Birling says from this point is pre-discredited. If he\'s wrong about the Titanic, he\'s wrong about "no war," he\'s wrong about labour relations, and crucially, he\'s wrong about social responsibility. Priestley uses one historical fact to demolish an entire worldview.',
      context: 'The Titanic was a symbol of Edwardian confidence in technology, progress and capitalism \u2014 an "unsinkable" ship built for profit that lacked enough lifeboats. Priestley chose it deliberately because it represents the hubris of Birling\'s entire class. The 1945 audience would also recognise Birling\'s prediction of "no war" as equally catastrophic \u2014 they had lived through two.',
