      devices: ['imagery', 'pathos'],
      analysis: '"Solitary child" echoes "solitary as an oyster" \u2014 the narrator links adult isolation to childhood abandonment, explaining the shell without excusing it. "Neglected" \u2014 passive voice: the child did not choose loneliness; it was imposed on him. "Left there still" \u2014 the present tense "still" is devastating. The pain is not past; it lives in the adult Scrooge now. This is pathos at its most effective: the reader\'s sympathy for the abandoned boy complicates their judgement of the miserable old man. Dickens\' technique is to make Scrooge pitiable before making him redeemable. Structurally, Stave 2 provides the psychological origin story that makes Stave 5\'s transformation believable \u2014 we believe he can become warm because we see he once was.',
      context: 'Dickens himself was sent to work in Warren\'s Blacking Factory at age 12 while his father was in debtors\' prison. This scene is partly autobiographical \u2014 the shame and loneliness of childhood abandonment haunted Dickens his entire life. He understood that cruelty is often the product of cruelty received.',
