      analysis: '"Idol" \u2014 an object of religious worship, invoking the biblical prohibition against idolatry. Money has become Scrooge\'s god. "Displaced" \u2014 pushed out, replaced: Belle didn\'t leave Scrooge; money pushed her away. "Golden" \u2014 simultaneously the colour of gold (wealth) and bitterly ironic (golden should mean precious, blessed). Belle names the exact moment love died: not through dramatic betrayal but gradual displacement by greed. Structurally, this scene is the emotional turning point of Stave 2 \u2014 Scrooge watching himself lose the only person who loved him. The Ghost forces him to witness the consequences of choices he can no longer undo. This motivates his later transformation: by Stave 4, he knows what he has already lost.',
      context: 'The biblical commandment against worshipping golden idols (the Golden Calf) would resonate powerfully with Victorian Christian readers. Dickens argues that capitalism can become a religion \u2014 with wealth as its sole value, profit as its prayer, and the poor as its sacrifice. Belle\'s departure shows the personal cost of this false worship.',
