      analysis: '"Every one" \u2014 universal, inclusive, no exceptions. Tim blesses those who harm his family as readily as those who help it. His goodness is effortless, unconditional, and utterly without resentment. "God bless us" \u2014 invoking divine blessing on humanity, not requesting material help. The exclamation is joyful, not desperate. Dickens uses a disabled, impoverished child to embody the moral ideal that the wealthy, educated, powerful Scrooge cannot achieve. This is deliberate structural irony: the person with the least has the most to give. Structurally, "God bless us, every one" returns as the novella\'s final line \u2014 spoken by the narrator in Stave 5, confirming that Tim survives and that Scrooge has embraced Tim\'s philosophy of universal generosity.',
      context: 'Tiny Tim represents the innocent victims of social neglect \u2014 children who suffer for the economic decisions of adults. Dickens makes him maximally sympathetic (disabled, loving, brave, dying) to force middle-class readers to feel the human cost of poverty. Tim\'s blessing is Dickens\' moral thesis: compassion must be universal and unconditional.',
