      devices: ['imagery', 'motif', 'foreshadowing'],
      analysis: '"Vacant seat" \u2014 absence made physically visible. "Crutch without an owner" \u2014 the object outlasts the child, and its continued presence makes the loss more painful, not less. "Carefully preserved" \u2014 the family keeps the crutch out of love, turning a medical aid into a memorial. This is Dickens weaponising sentimentality with full knowledge of what he\'s doing. The Ghost foreshadows Tim\'s death not through statement but through imagery \u2014 making the reader construct the death in their own imagination, which is more devastating than being told. Structurally, this vision motivates Scrooge\'s transformation: he cannot bear the future the Ghost shows him. The "vacant seat" imagery returns in Stave 4 with Scrooge\'s own empty chair \u2014 nobody mourns him, while Tim is mourned by everyone.',
      context: 'Dickens uses emotional manipulation as a political weapon \u2014 he wants the reader to feel Tim\'s preventable death as a personal loss, then channel that grief into political action. Victorian child mortality was staggeringly high among the poor: one in five children died before age five. Tim\'s potential death is not melodrama but demographic reality.',
