      analysis: 'Scrooge\'s own words from Stave 1 hurled back at him \u2014 the most devastating use of dramatic irony in the novella. In Stave 1, "surplus population" was abstract economic theory; now it refers to a specific, named, dying child Scrooge has met, played with, and begun to care about. The structural irony is crushing: Scrooge already pronounced Tim\'s death sentence before knowing he existed. "Decrease" \u2014 the same clinical verb that sounded merely callous in Stave 1 now sounds monstrous. Dickens\' technique is to force abstract ideology to confront human reality. The Ghost doesn\'t argue against Malthus; he simply applies Scrooge\'s own logic to someone Scrooge loves. The argument collapses on contact with reality.',
      context: 'This is Dickens\' central political technique throughout the novella: translate abstract economic language into specific human consequence. "Surplus population" sounds reasonable in a parliamentary debate; applied to Tiny Tim, it becomes murder. Dickens forces the reader to make the same journey: from comfortable theory to uncomfortable reality.',
