      analysis: 'Allegory at its most powerful: abstract social problems personified as starving, hideous children hiding beneath the Spirit\'s robe. "Beware" \u2014 imperative directed simultaneously at Scrooge and the reader. "Most of all beware this boy" \u2014 Ignorance is more dangerous than Want because it prevents solutions: you cannot fix what you refuse to see. The imagery is deliberately horrifying \u2014 "yellow, meagre, ragged, scowling, wolfish" \u2014 Dickens wants the reader to feel revulsion, then recognise that these are children society created. Structurally, this is the novella\'s most overtly political moment, the point where Dickens drops allegory and speaks directly to Victorian society through the Ghost.',
      context: 'Dickens addresses his readers without disguise: Ignorance and Want are not individual failures but systemic products of inequality. He deliberately places this warning in the mouth of a supernatural being to give it prophetic weight. "Beware this boy" \u2014 the Ghost warns that an ignorant population will eventually destroy the society that neglected them. Dickens was prophetic: social unrest was a constant Victorian fear.',
