      devices: ['rhetorical_question', 'antithesis'],
      analysis: 'The crucial distinction between "Will be" (deterministic) and "May be" (conditional). Scrooge asks whether the future is fixed or changeable. This is the novella\'s philosophical turning point: the moment he accepts that transformation is possible. The rhetorical question is directed at himself as much as the Spirit. "Shadows" \u2014 not the future itself but projections of it, implying they can be altered. Structurally, this is the "dark night of the soul" \u2014 the moment of deepest despair that precedes conversion. Every conversion narrative requires this crisis point, and Dickens places it with mathematical precision between the horror of Stave 4 and the joy of Stave 5.',
      context: 'Dickens structures A Christmas Carol as a conversion narrative modelled on Christian redemption: sin \u2192 recognition \u2192 repentance \u2192 grace. This question is the moment of repentance. Dickens argues that free will and moral choice can overcome any past \u2014 a profoundly optimistic philosophy that the novella\'s structure enacts. The past is shown (Stave 2) but cannot be changed; the future is shown (Stave 4) and CAN be changed. The present (Stave 3) is where the choice is made.',
