      devices: ['metaphor', 'motif'],
      analysis: '"In my heart" \u2014 internalised, not performative or temporary. "All the year" \u2014 permanent transformation, not seasonal charity. "Try" \u2014 the most important word: humble, human, realistic. Dickens makes the promise believable by making it imperfect. A lesser writer would have Scrooge promise absolute perfection; Dickens gives him "try," which is both more modest and more moving. "Honour" \u2014 to treat with deep reverence, elevating Christmas from a calendar date to a moral philosophy. Structurally, "I will" (future) contrasts with "I was" (past) throughout Stave 4 \u2014 Scrooge is rewriting his own future tense.',
      context: 'Dickens argues that "Christmas spirit" is a metaphor for year-round compassion, generosity, and community. The novella was published at Christmas but its message is deliberately universal. The subtitle "A Ghost Story of Christmas" signals the genre, but the moral content applies to every day. Dickens hoped to do for his readers what the Ghosts did for Scrooge.',
