      analysis: 'Pathetic fallacy \u2014 the weather mirrors Scrooge\'s internal transformation. "No fog, no mist" \u2014 negative construction clearing away the obstacles of Stave 1 (where fog was oppressive and blinding). "Clear, bright, jovial, stirring" \u2014 four adjectives tumbling out in rapid succession, as if the narrator can barely contain them. "Cold" \u2014 crucially, the temperature hasn\'t changed. The world is the same; Scrooge\'s perception of it has transformed. Dickens argues that moral transformation changes everything without changing anything external. Structurally, the weather is the novella\'s most consistent metaphor: Stave 1\'s fog = moral blindness, Stave 5\'s clarity = moral sight. Same cold, different eyes.',
      context: 'The weather in Stave 1 was described as oppressive, biting, and penetrating. Stave 5\'s weather is exactly the same temperature but experienced as invigorating. Dickens makes a philosophical argument through pathetic fallacy: perspective determines experience. Poverty doesn\'t change \u2014 but how society responds to it can.',
