      analysis: 'Christmas reframed as theft. "Picking a man\'s pocket" \u2014 paying Bob Cratchit for a day off is, in Scrooge\'s moral universe, robbery. He monetises everything, including human rest, kindness, and celebration. "Every twenty-fifth" \u2014 the date is stripped of spiritual meaning and presented as a recurring financial crime. The metaphor reveals complete moral inversion: generosity is theft, kindness is weakness, rest is laziness. Structurally, this connects to "Are there no prisons?" \u2014 both lines reveal a worldview where human needs are economic losses. By Stave 5, Scrooge raises Bob\'s wages and buys the Cratchits a turkey \u2014 the direct reversal of this pocket-picking metaphor.',
      context: 'Bob Cratchit earned 15 shillings a week \u2014 barely enough to feed a family. Scrooge resents paying him for Christmas Day. Dickens exposes how utilitarian capitalism views workers\' basic rights as personal losses for employers. The novella was published when workers had no paid holidays at all.',
