      analysis: 'The narrator\'s opening line \u2014 deliberately colloquial, warm, humorous. "Dead as a door-nail" is a well-worn clich\u00e9, which the narrator immediately acknowledges and playfully interrogates ("I don\'t mean to say that I know, of my own knowledge, what there is particularly dead about a door-nail"). Dickens establishes the narrator as a character: chatty, self-aware, trustworthy, and entertaining. By confirming Marley\'s death so emphatically, Dickens makes the ghost\'s later appearance more shocking \u2014 the supernatural breaks into a narrative that began in cosy domesticity. Structurally, opening with death and closing with life mirrors Scrooge\'s journey from spiritual death to moral rebirth.',
